aph of the output text [records: Entities (1, 2, 3), Claims (2, 5), Relationships (10, 12)]\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n5,ABILA CITY PARK,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n37,ABILA CITY PARK,POK RALLY,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n38,ABILA CITY PARK,POK,POK is holding a rally in Abila City Park\n39,ABILA CITY PARK,POKRALLY,The POKRally is taking place at Abila City Park\n40,ABILA CITY PARK,CENTRAL BULLETIN,Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park\n\nOutput:\n{\n    \"title\": \"Abila City Park and POK Rally\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community revolves around the Abila City Park, which is the location of the POK rally. The park has relationships with POK, POKRALLY, and Central Bulletin, all\nof which are associated with the rally event.\",\n    \"rating\": 5.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact rating is moderate due to the potential for unrest or conflict during the POK rally.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Abila City Park as the central location\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Abila City Park is the central entity in this community, serving as the location for the POK rally. This park is the common link between all other\nentities, suggesting its significance in the community. The park's association with the rally could potentially lead to issues such as public disorder or conflict, depending on the\nnature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. [records: Entities (5), Relationships (37, 38, 39, 40)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POK's role in the community\",\n            \"explanation\": \"POK is another key entity in this community, being the organizer of the rally at Abila City Park. The nature of POK and its rally could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on their objectives and the reactions they provoke. The relationship between POK and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this community.\n[records: Relationships (38)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POKRALLY as a significant event\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The POKRALLY is a significant event taking place at Abila City Park. This event is a key factor in the community's dynamics and could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on the nature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. The relationship between the rally and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this\ncommunity. [records: Relationships (39)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Role of Central Bulletin\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park. This suggests that the event has attracted media attention, which could\namplify its impact on the community. The role of Central Bulletin could be significant in shaping public perception of the event and the entities involved. [records: Relationships\n(40)]\"\n        }\n    ]\n\n}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n----Reports-----\nid,full_content\r\n27,\"# AUTHOR, AI POLICY, and DISCLOSURE in Academic Publishing\n\nThe community centers around the AUTHOR, who is subject to a complex network of AI policies, disclosure requirements, and ethical guidelines. Key entities include AI POLICY, DISCLOSURE, and various publishers like Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley. These entities interact through relationships that enforce transparency, accountability, and ethical use of AI in academic publishing. The AUTHOR must disclose AI usage, ensure originality, and comply with institutional and journal-specific rules.\n\n## AUTHOR as the central figure in AI governance\n\nThe AUTHOR is the primary stakeholder in the academic publishing process, responsible for ensuring the ethical and transparent use of AI tools. This includes disclosing AI usage, verifying the accuracy of AI-generated content, and maintaining the integrity of their work. The AUTHOR's role is defined by a set of responsibilities that align with AI policies and disclosure requirements across major publishers such as Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley. [records: Entities (7), Relationships (125, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\n\n## AI POLICY as a regulatory framework for AI use\n\nAI POLICY serves as a regulatory framework that guides authors on the ethical and transparent use of AI in academic publishing. It mandates that authors disclose the use of AI technologies, including specific tools, their purposes, and the extent of human oversight. These policies are enforced by journals and publishers, such as Elsevier, which require authors to follow strict guidelines on AI use during manuscript preparation and submission. The interaction between AI POLICY and the AUTHOR ensures that AI integration does not compromise academic integrity. [records: Entities (125), Relationships (125, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\n\n## DISCLOSURE as a mechanism for transparency\n\nDISCLOSURE is a critical mechanism that requires authors to reveal the use of AI tools in their manuscripts, ensuring transparency and accountability. This includes detailing the specific AI tools used, their functions, and the reasons for their application. Publishers such as Emerald, Wiley, and Taylor & Francis have established clear disclosure requirements, often mandating that authors include this information in the methods section, acknowledgment section, or online appendix. The relationship between DISCLOSURE and the AUTHOR underscores the importance of openness in the integration of AI into scholarly work. [records: Entities (21), Relationships (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126)]\n\n## Ethical obligations of AUTHORS regarding AI use\n\nAUTHORS are ethically obligated to ensure the accuracy, originality, and integrity of their work, even when using AI tools. This includes verifying the reliability of AI-generated content, avoiding plagiarism, and adhering to citation standards. Ethical guidelines from organizations like ASHA and BERA emphasize the need for responsible AI use, while publishers such as BMJ and Springer Nature require authors to maintain the authenticity of their research. The interplay between ETHICAL USE and the AUTHOR highlights the shared responsibility of maintaining academic standards in an AI-integrated environment. [records: Entities (113, 112, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150)]\n\n## Institutional accountability in AI governance\n\nInstitutional accountability is a key aspect of AI governance in academic publishing, with publishers like Elsevier, Emerald, and Wiley enforcing strict policies on AI use. These institutions require authors to disclose AI usage, verify the accuracy of AI-generated content, and ensure that AI tools do not infringe on intellectual property rights. Additionally, journals such as BMJ and Taylor & Francis have specific guidelines that mandate transparency in AI-assisted research, reinforcing the role of institutional frameworks in maintaining academic integrity. [records: Entities (7, 21, 113), Relationships (126, 145, 153, 146, 151, 143, 140, 150, 118, 129)]\n\n## Impact of AI on authorship and originality\n\nThe integration of AI into academic publishing raises concerns about authorship and originality. While AI tools can assist in tasks such as writing, data analysis, and image generation, they cannot be listed as authors. Authors are responsible for ensuring that AI-generated content is properly cited and that the originality of their work is maintained. Policies from organizations like ICMJE and publishers such as Emerald emphasize that AI should not replace the core intellectual contributions of the author. This relationship between AUTHORSHIP and ORIGINALITY reinforces the need for clear boundaries in AI-assisted research. [records: Entities (134, 102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118)]\n\n## Challenges in AI disclosure and verification\n\nDisclosing and verifying AI usage presents significant challenges for authors, particularly in ensuring that all AI-generated content is accurately attributed and verified. Some journals, such as Emerald, require authors to provide specific prompts used with AI tools, while others, like Wiley, mandate that AI-generated content be cited following specific formatting guidelines. The complexity of these requirements highlights the need for standardized disclosure practices across academic publishing platforms. [records: Entities (21, 148, 156), Relationships (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126)]\n\n## Role of peer review in AI governance\n\nPeer reviewers play a crucial role in AI governance by ensuring that AI usage is disclosed and that the integrity of the research is maintained. Some journals require peer reviewers to disclose the use of AI tools in their evaluations, reinforcing the importance of transparency throughout the publication process. Editors also play a key role in enforcing AI disclosure policies, ensuring that authors adhere to institutional and journal-specific guidelines. This relationship between PEER REVIEW PROCESS and DISCLOSURE highlights the collaborative effort required to uphold academic standards in AI-integrated research. [records: Entities (102, 101, 10, 134, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126), Relationships (187, 157, 319)]\n\n## Legal and ethical implications of AI in publishing\n\nThe use of AI in academic publishing has legal and ethical implications, particularly concerning copyright, privacy, and data security. Authors must ensure that AI tools do not infringe on the rights of others, including copyright holders, and that sensitive data is protected. Policies from organizations like GDPR and publishers such as Taylor & Francis emphasize the need for responsible AI use, including safeguards against data breaches and unauthorized access. These considerations highlight the broader legal and ethical dimensions of AI governance in academic publishing. [records: Entities (119, 123, 128, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126, 145), Relationships (119, 123, 128, 129, 122, 140, 150, 118, 126, 145)]\n\n## Future directions in AI policy development\n\nAs AI continues to evolve, academic publishing institutions are likely to refine their policies to address emerging challenges. This includes developing more standardized disclosure requirements, enhancing AI detection tools, and promoting greater collaboration between authors, editors, and reviewers. The ongoing dialogue between AI POLICY, DISCLOSURE, and the AUTHOR reflects the dynamic nature of AI governance in academic publishing, with a growing emphasis on transparency, accountability, and ethical responsibility. [records: Entities (125, 21, 113, 102, 101, 10, 1\"\r\n\n\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n44,CITATION,\"CITATION refers to the act of acknowledging sources used in a manuscript, including references to other works, studies, or AI-generated content. It involves citing relevant academic sources, such as specific studies or language models, in accordance with journal guidelines. The process may be influenced by AI-assisted tools during manuscript preparation, and authors are required to ensure the accuracy of all citations. This includes verifying that references are not generated by AI tools unless explicitly acknowledged. CITATION is essential for maintaining academic integrity, particularly when AI tools contribute significantly to the work or when AI-generated examples or content are included. It also encompasses the referencing of all quoted material, whether human- or machine-generated, and requires careful monitoring to uphold scholarly standards.\",8\r\n45,SOURCE,\"The entity \"\"SOURCE\"\" refers to the origin of information or content used in a manuscript, which may include both traditional academic references and AI-generated material. It encompasses original materials or works that are referenced in academic work and must be properly cited, verified, and attributed, especially when derived from or influenced by AI tools. The SOURCE is critical in ensuring academic integrity, as it requires authors to maintain transparency and accountability in their use of AI-assisted or AI-generated content. This includes proper citation and verification processes to uphold the standards of scholarly communication and ethical research practices.\",7\r\n16,ORIGINALITY,\"Originality is a fundamental principle in academic publishing, defined as the quality of being new, unique, and not copied from other sources. It is the responsibility of authors to ensure that their work meets this standard, even when utilizing AI tools such as large language models (LLMs) or other AI technologies during manuscript preparation. This requirement extends to the exclusion of substantially AI-generated content, which must not form the core of the submitted work. Originality is essential for maintaining the integrity and credibility of academic research, and it remains a key criterion in the evaluation and acceptance of scholarly publications. Authors are expected to uphold this standard by actively verifying the originality of their contributions, regardless of the extent to which AI tools may be employed in the research or writing process.\",7\r\n57,DUP,\"A publisher of academic journals that prohibits the submission of work substantially written by generative AI and LLMs\"\"\",4\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n140,AUTHOR,CITATION,\"Authors must ensure that all citations in their manuscripts are accurate, verified, and aligned with their expertise and research, and they should not rely on AI tools for generating citations. Additionally, authors are required to cite the use of large language models (LLMs) in their work following specific formatting guidelines, ensuring transparency and adherence to academic integrity standards.\",67\r\n141,AUTHOR,SOURCE,\"Authors must ensure that all sources are properly cited and verified, with particular attention to the accuracy of sources used in their work, especially when AI tools are involved. This responsibility applies to both the AUTHOR and the SOURCE, as the integrity of academic publishing depends on the proper attribution and validation of information. The AUTHOR is tasked with maintaining scholarly rigor by confirming the reliability of the SOURCE, particularly in contexts where AI-generated or assisted content may introduce uncertainties.\",66\r\n104,AUTHOR,ORIGINALITY,\"The entity \"\"AUTHOR\"\" is central to the academic publishing process, with a clear and consistent responsibility to ensure the \"\"ORIGINALITY\"\" of their work. This obligation remains intact even when authors utilize AI tools or AI-generated content in the preparation of their manuscripts. Authors are required to maintain the originality of their contributions, avoiding reliance on AI tools to generate substantial portions of their work. The emphasis across all descriptions is on the author's accountability for the integrity and originality of their scholarly output, regardless of the extent to which AI technologies are employed during the writing process. This reflects a broader policy framework that upholds academic standards and ethical practices in the context of emerging AI-driven research and publication tools.\",66\r\n60,AI TECHNOLOGY,CITATION,\"AI technology may generate content that requires proper citation, and authors must ensure all sources are acknowledged. Citations may be affected by AI-assisted processes, requiring careful review and disclosure. Together, AI technology and citation practices intersect in the academic publishing ecosystem, where the use of artificial intelligence in content generation raises important questions about authorship, accountability, and scholarly integrity. As AI-assisted tools become more integrated into research and writing workflows, the responsibility falls on researchers to maintain transparency, disclose the role of AI in their work, and adhere to established citation standards. This dynamic highlights the evolving relationship between emerging technologies and traditional academic norms, emphasizing the need for clear guidelines and ethical frameworks to govern the use of AI in scholarly communication.\",56\r\n61,AI TECHNOLOGY,SOURCE,\"The use of AI technology in academic publishing may involve external sources, which must be properly cited to ensure academic integrity. Additionally, sources cited in a manuscript may be influenced by AI-assisted processes, necessitating transparency in the research and writing workflow. This highlights the interplay between AI technology and source materials within the academic publishing ecosystem, emphasizing the need for ethical and transparent practices when integrating AI tools into scholarly work.\",55\r\n37,AI TECHNOLOGY,ORIGINALITY,\"AI technology is generally recognized as incapable of producing original work that meets the standards of academic publishing. As such, it is emphasized that AI technology must not compromise the originality of academic work, and authors are required to verify the authenticity of content they produce. Furthermore, authors must ensure that their content remains unique, reinforcing the importance of human oversight in maintaining the integrity and originality of academic output.\",55\r\n286,ORIGINALITY,AI POLICY,\"AI policies uphold the principle of originality, prohibiting the submission of work substantially written by AI tools\",42\r\n364,AI POLICY,DUP,DUP has developed an AI policy to guide authors on the ethical and responsible use of AI in academic publishing,39\r\n325,DISCLOSURE,CITATION,\"Authors must cite sources properly, including AI-generated content, to maintain transparency\",36\r\n326